:PNLGRP.
.*---------------------------------------------------------------------
:HELP   NAME=GETDATE.Retrieve Current Date
:P.This command was created to retrieve the current job or system
date. Unqualified it returns the job date as a decimal field that is
declared as LEN(8,0).
:P.The command also has options to retrieve the date in different formats
and to receive parts of the date like the year or month.
:P.The command can also be used to get previous and future dates. There
are options to add and subtract days, works days, months and years.
:P.The command be used to do date math on a passed date as well. The
STRDATE parameter allows passing in a different start date. Enter *PASS
as the option and a field for INDATE will be allowed. The INDATE field
tells the program to use the date passed as the start date. Then the
addition and subtraction options will be based on the passed date. The
passed date must be a character value in YYYYMMDD format.
:P.This is used in CL programs so you do not have
to declare multiple fields to retrieve the date and then do date
conversion.
:H2.Example 1:
:P.The following example pulls the job date in YYYYMMDD format as
a decimal value.
:P.GETDATE &#DATE
:H2.Example 2:
:P.The following example pulls the year, month and day as seperate
character fields.
:P.GETDATE CHRYYYY(&YYYY) CHRMM(&MM) CHRDD(&DD)
:H2.Example 3:
:P.The following example gets the system date in YYYYMMDD format as
a decimal value.
:P.GETDATE &#DATE STRDATE(*SYS)
:H2.Example 4:
:P.The following example pulls the previous work day in YYYYMMDD
format.
:P.GETDATE &PRIDATE SUBWRKDAY(1)
:H2.Example 5:
:P.The following example shows how to do date math using the
command. This example add 5 work days to date 20210101. This is
done by passing a date in and using the ADDWRKDAYS option.
:P.GETDATE &TODATE ADDWRKDAY(5) STRDATE(*PASS) INDATE(20210101)
:P.Since 2021-01-01 is a Friday the command will return 20210108
in the variable &TODATE.
:P.The remainder of this help text lists each format available.
:EHELP.
.*---------------------------------------------------------------------
:HELP   NAME='GETDATE/DEC8'.Decimal 8 Digit Date - YYYYMMDD
:XH3.DEC8 Decimal 8 Digit Date - YYYYMMDD
:P.Specifies the CL variable to return the date value to. The variable
must be defined as *DEC LEN(8 0). The date will be returned in
YYYYMMDD format.
:EHELP.
